Section2.Para:
The effect of pressure on the electronic structure of MgZn2 has been also studied. The equilibrium density of states (DOS) and the pressure dependence of DOS are intuitively illustrated in Fig. 3. The total DOS (TDOS) and partial DOS (PDOS) of MgZn2 in the vicinity of the Fermi level at 0 GPa are plotted in Fig. 3(a), where the zero energy in the plotted figure corresponds to the Fermi level. The obtained value of the TDOS at the Fermi level N(E

                    F
                  ) is 0.294 electrons/eV/atom for MgZn2 from the GGA calculation, which agrees extremely well with the precious experimental data [37] and other theoretical results [10]. It is also observed that the profile of TDOS is similar to the results reported in the previous literature [13, 37], which indicates the calculations of electronic structure of MgZn2 are reliable. The TDOS in Fig. 3(a) shows that there is no energy gap near the Fermi level for MgZn2, implying the metallic behavior of MgZn2. The obtained metallic behavior in the present work is consistent with the general characteristic of Laves phases [38]. The TDOS below the Fermi level may be roughly divided into two parts. At the low energy region, ranging from −10 eV to −5.0 eV, the main bonding peaks are predominantly derived from the Zn 3d orbital, which contributes to the TDOS in the region. This part is followed by a region dominated by Mg 3s, Mg 2p, and Zn 3p orbitals (ranging from about −5.0 eV to the Fermi level). There exists a weaker hybridization between Zn 4s and Mg sp orbitals above the Fermi level, which indicates the existence of covalent bonding in MgZn2 crystal. In addition, we find that the number of bonding electrons per atom of MgZn2 is 8.664 at the low energy region (–10.0 eV to 0 eV), which is in good agreement with the values in [12] and [13]. We also investigate the TDOS and PDOS near the Fermi level of MgZn2 at 25 and 50 GPa, and the results are plotted in Figs. 3(b) and 3(c). The obtained N(E

                    F
                  ) at 25 and 50 GPa is 0.212 and 0.177 electrons/eV/atom, respectively. It is found that the N(E

                    F
                  ) decreases by about 39.62 % from 0 GPa to 50 GPa, which indicates that the applied pressure is beneficial to the stability of MgZn2. The shifting of Mg 3s and Mg 2p orbitals towards the low energy region can be observed, and the intensity of Mg 3s orbital gradually increases with increasing pressure. Besides, the Zn 3d orbital exhibits a slightly broadening as well as the decrease of its intensity with the increase of pressure, while the Zn 4s and Zn 3p orbitals show little change. These results may be explained by the variations of the spacing between atoms as well as the overlap of wave functions under compression. Interestingly, it can be seen that the peaks of the TDOS in about −8.0 eV split into some small peaks and become wider under compression. These phenomena can be explained by the delocalization among the bonding atoms in MgZn2 crystal. Furthermore, it is observed that the TDOS of MgZn2 exhibits a certain departure from the Fermi level with the applied pressure. This results exhibit a difference from our previous study of MgCu2 [39]. The difference may be attributed to that the change of interaction potentials and the zigzag pattern of hexagonal stacking sequence under compression. Finally, the dependence of DOS of MgZn2 on pressure can be served as a representative for high-pressure Laves phase with C14-type structure. 

